      "side": 1,
      "message": "This caught me off guard. You don\u0027t need to change anything, but to explain what\u0027s happening here:\n\nSkSL works like GLSL - vector types are (mathematically) amorphous, they might be row vectors, or column vectors. So you can do (Matrix * Vector), which is common, or (Vector * Matrix), which is not so common. Seeing (V*M) usually sends up a red flag, because it suggests that your matrix is transposed from normal mathematical form...\n\nThis is made worse because GL uses column-major memory order for matrix uniforms, so it\u0027s easy to have a matrix in row-major order, upload it to GL, then \"fix\" it by multiplying on the left.(That\u0027s what\u0027s happening here). It\u0027s not wrong - it\u0027s just a little confusing. As long as you just do a single operation like this, it\u0027s not too bad - if you start working with multiple matrices, it\u0027s better to have them laid out correctly, or the multiplication order gets really confusing.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 50,
        "startChar": 12,
        "endLine": 50,
        "endChar": 39
      },
      "revId": "b2e12a357ccf930504541969603b524b6a5ce798",
